Members of the Flying Squad raided a farm in the rural areas of Drakenstein and discovered large quantities of Dagga. The raid in Paarl at Western Cape comes after police in the lead operations to clean the province of any drugs. According to police spokesperson in the Western Cape Andrè Traut the burst occurred on Friday. “Our pursuit to eradicate the lucrative drug market in this province  members of the Flying Squad discovered a cannabis harvesting and manufacturing operation in the Drakenstein rural area of Paarl,” said Traut. Traut said the discovery led to further searches to be conducted on the farm premises. The search led to the arrest of 25 suspects who are believed to be aged between 18 to 55 years. They discovered dagga plants as well as large quantities of prepared the drug ready to be sold. “Due to the substantial quantities, the estimated value of the drugs is yet to be determined,” Traut added. The suspects are facing charges of dealing in drugs and more arrests pending investigations may occur. Traut said they expected to appear in court on Monday. The Provincial Commissioner of the Western Cape police, Lt Gen Thembisile Patekile commended the units responsible for the operation and issued a stern warning to drug dealers that their illegal trade will remain high on our policing priority list.  ALSO READ: Three bank teller’s accomplices convicted of theft and money laundering